**Type:** academic

**Category:** Philosophy of Religion / Revelation / Faith and Knowledge
**Abstract:** Essay critiquing the traditional intellectualist understanding of revelation as divine transmission of knowledge requiring intellectual assent. Argues against Aquinas's view that faith is believing propositions on divine authority, proposing instead a practical model of faith as obedient consent exemplified by Abraham's response to God's call. Distinguishes between "consent to" (practical) and "assent to" (intellectual) as fundamentally different acts.
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Central essay articulating Monasterio's critique of the intellectualization of faith; directly supports his thesis about the loss of practical/narrative understanding of religious knowledge.

